/* KCNA content - Cloud Native Architecture (12% of exam; includes Observability). Auto-generated. */
KCNA.register({"id": "architecture", "name": "Cloud Native Architecture", "weight": 12, "notes": [{"id": "architecture-note-1", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Cloud native fundamentals and the CNCF landscape", "title": "Cloud Native Fundamentals & the CNCF Landscape", "html": "<p>Cloud native is an approach to building and running scalable applications in modern, dynamic environments like public, private, and hybrid clouds.</p><ul><li><strong>CNCF definition pillars:</strong> containers, service meshes, microservices, immutable infrastructure, and declarative APIs.</li><li><strong>Goal:</strong> systems that are <strong>resilient</strong>, <strong>manageable</strong>, and <strong>observable</strong>, allowing frequent, low-effort, high-impact changes.</li><li><strong>Automation</strong> (robust automation + CI/CD) lets engineers make changes predictably with minimal toil.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Key characteristics:</strong> <strong>loosely coupled</strong> services, <strong>resilient/self-healing</strong>, <strong>elastic/scalable</strong> on demand, <strong>portable</strong> across clouds, and <strong>declarative</strong> (state desired, controllers reconcile).</li><li><strong>Immutable infrastructure:</strong> you replace components rather than patch them in place; new image = new deployment.</li><li><strong>Speed & efficiency</strong> are the business drivers (faster time to market, better resource use).</li></ul><ul><li><strong>CNCF</strong> = Cloud Native Computing Foundation, part of the <strong>Linux Foundation</strong>, vendor-neutral home for cloud native open source projects.</li><li><strong>Kubernetes</strong> was the first CNCF project to <strong>graduate</strong>.</li><li>The <strong>CNCF Landscape</strong> is a map of projects/products grouped by category (orchestration, observability, networking, storage, security, etc.).</li></ul><p><em>Exam tip:</em> Memorize the five CNCF pillars and the three qualities (resilient, manageable, observable). Cloud native is about <strong>how</strong> you build, not just running in \"the cloud.\"</p>"}, {"id": "architecture-note-2", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Autoscaling (Horizontal Pod Autoscaler, Vertical Pod Autoscaler, Cluster Autoscaler)", "title": "Autoscaling: HPA, VPA & Cluster Autoscaler", "html": "<p>Kubernetes scales workloads automatically at two levels: pods (HPA/VPA) and nodes (Cluster Autoscaler).</p><ul><li><strong>Horizontal Pod Autoscaler (HPA):</strong> adds/removes <strong>pod replicas</strong> based on metrics (CPU, memory, or custom/external metrics). Scales <em>out/in</em>. Implemented as <code>HorizontalPodAutoscaler</code>; targets a Deployment/ReplicaSet/StatefulSet.</li><li>HPA needs the <strong>Metrics Server</strong> to read resource usage.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Vertical Pod Autoscaler (VPA):</strong> adjusts <strong>CPU/memory requests and limits</strong> of pods. Scales <em>up/down</em> the size of each pod, not the count.</li><li>VPA usually <strong>recreates pods</strong> to apply new resource values (causing restarts). Not a core component; installed separately.</li><li><em>Exam tip:</em> Do <strong>not</strong> use HPA and VPA on the same CPU/memory metric simultaneously — they conflict.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Cluster Autoscaler (CA):</strong> adds/removes <strong>worker nodes</strong> from the cluster. Adds nodes when pods are <strong>Pending</strong> (unschedulable due to insufficient resources); removes underutilized nodes.</li><li>CA works with the <strong>cloud provider</strong> (node groups / autoscaling groups) and operates at the infrastructure level.</li></ul><p><em>Exam tip — which does what:</em> HPA = more pods, VPA = bigger pods, CA = more nodes. <strong>Karpenter</strong> is a newer, flexible node autoscaler alternative to Cluster Autoscaler.</p>"}, {"id": "architecture-note-3", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Serverless and Knative / Function-as-a-Service", "title": "Serverless, Knative & FaaS", "html": "<p>Serverless lets developers run code without managing servers, paying only for actual execution while the platform handles scaling.</p><ul><li><strong>Serverless</strong> abstracts away infrastructure provisioning; the cloud/platform auto-scales, including <strong>scale-to-zero</strong> when idle.</li><li><strong>FaaS (Function-as-a-Service):</strong> deploy small, event-driven <strong>functions</strong> that run on demand (e.g., AWS Lambda, Google Cloud Functions, Azure Functions).</li><li>Serverless is broader than FaaS — it also includes managed backends and event services.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Knative</strong> is the CNCF project that adds <strong>serverless</strong> capabilities on top of Kubernetes.</li><li><strong>Knative Serving:</strong> request-driven autoscaling (incl. <strong>scale-to-zero</strong>), revisions, and traffic splitting for deployments.</li><li><strong>Knative Eventing:</strong> event-driven architecture using <strong>CloudEvents</strong>, with sources, brokers, and triggers to route events.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>CloudEvents</strong> = a CNCF spec for describing event data in a common, vendor-neutral format.</li><li>Other CNCF serverless projects: <strong>OpenFaaS</strong>, <strong>KEDA</strong> (event-driven autoscaling, can drive HPA + scale-to-zero).</li></ul><p><em>Exam tips:</em> Knative runs <strong>on Kubernetes</strong> and brings serverless/scale-to-zero. Benefits: cost efficiency and reduced ops; trade-offs: <strong>cold starts</strong> and potential vendor lock-in. KEDA = Kubernetes Event-Driven Autoscaling.</p>"}, {"id": "architecture-note-4", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "CNCF community, governance and project maturity levels (Sandbox, Incubating, Graduated)", "title": "CNCF Governance & Maturity Levels", "html": "<p>The CNCF organizes projects by maturity to signal adoption and stability, and uses open governance bodies to steer them.</p><ul><li><strong>Sandbox:</strong> earliest stage — experimental/early projects with potential. Low barrier to entry; for innovation and early adopters.</li><li><strong>Incubating:</strong> growing adoption and a healthy contributor community; used in production by a few organizations; passed a due-diligence review.</li><li><strong>Graduated:</strong> highest maturity — proven, widely adopted, stable. Requirements include the <strong>CII/OpenSSF Best Practices badge</strong>, committers from multiple organizations, and adoption by many users. Examples: <strong>Kubernetes, Prometheus, Envoy, etcd, Helm</strong>.</li></ul><ul><li>Maturity is assessed via the <strong>CNCF TOC (Technical Oversight Committee)</strong>, which provides technical leadership and votes projects between levels.</li><li><strong>Governing Board</strong> handles budget/marketing/business oversight; the <strong>End User Community</strong> represents adopting organizations.</li><li><strong>SIGs (Special Interest Groups)</strong> focus on areas (e.g., security, observability) and advise the TOC.</li></ul><ul><li>CNCF also runs <strong>certifications</strong> (KCNA, CKA, CKAD, CKS) and the <strong>Certified Kubernetes Conformance</strong> program for distributions.</li></ul><p><em>Exam tip — order to memorize:</em> <strong>Sandbox → Incubating → Graduated</strong> (increasing maturity). Know that Kubernetes and Prometheus are <strong>Graduated</strong>.</p>"}, {"id": "architecture-note-5", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Roles and personas in cloud native organizations", "title": "Roles & Personas in Cloud Native Orgs", "html": "<p>Cloud native shifts responsibilities toward shared ownership, automation, and breaking down silos between dev and ops.</p><ul><li><strong>Developer / Application Developer:</strong> writes and packages app code (often into containers); focuses on features and increasingly owns deployment too.</li><li><strong>DevOps Engineer:</strong> bridges dev and ops, builds <strong>CI/CD pipelines</strong>, automates delivery. <strong>DevOps</strong> is a culture/practice, not a single tool.</li><li><strong>Site Reliability Engineer (SRE):</strong> applies software engineering to operations; uses <strong>SLIs, SLOs, SLAs</strong> and <strong>error budgets</strong> to balance reliability vs. velocity.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Platform Engineer:</strong> builds <strong>internal developer platforms (IDP)</strong> and \"golden paths\" so developers can self-serve infrastructure.</li><li><strong>Cloud / Infrastructure Engineer:</strong> manages cloud resources and clusters, often via <strong>Infrastructure as Code (IaC)</strong>.</li><li><strong>Security Engineer / DevSecOps:</strong> shifts security \"left\" into the pipeline; secures supply chain, images, and runtime.</li><li><strong>Data Engineer / FinOps:</strong> data pipelines; FinOps optimizes and attributes cloud cost.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>GitOps</strong> practitioners use Git as the single source of truth for declarative deployments (e.g., Argo CD, Flux).</li></ul><p><em>Exam tips:</em> Know <strong>SLO vs SLA vs SLI</strong> and <strong>error budget</strong>. DevOps = culture of collaboration + automation; SRE = a concrete implementation of DevOps principles. Platform engineering reduces developer <strong>cognitive load</strong>.</p>"}, {"id": "architecture-note-6", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Open standards (OCI, CRI, CNI, CSI, SMI, OpenTelemetry)", "title": "Open Standards: OCI, CRI, CNI, CSI, SMI, OTel", "html": "<p>Open standards keep the cloud native ecosystem interoperable and vendor-neutral by defining common interfaces.</p><ul><li><strong>OCI (Open Container Initiative):</strong> standards for container <strong>image format</strong>, <strong>runtime</strong>, and <strong>distribution</strong>. Ensures images built once run on any compliant runtime (e.g., <strong>runc</strong>).</li><li><strong>CRI (Container Runtime Interface):</strong> Kubernetes-to-runtime API so the <strong>kubelet</strong> can use any compliant runtime (e.g., <strong>containerd</strong>, <strong>CRI-O</strong>). Dockershim was removed in <strong>v1.24</strong>.</li><li><strong>CNI (Container Network Interface):</strong> plugin standard for <strong>pod networking</strong> (IP assignment, connectivity). Examples: <strong>Calico, Cilium, Flannel, Weave</strong>.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>CSI (Container Storage Interface):</strong> standard for exposing <strong>storage</strong> systems to Kubernetes; enables third-party drivers for volumes/PersistentVolumes.</li><li><strong>SMI (Service Mesh Interface):</strong> a standard API for <strong>service meshes</strong> (traffic policy, telemetry, access control) so tooling works across meshes. Note: SMI was archived in 2023; <strong>Gateway API</strong> is increasingly relevant.</li><li><strong>OpenTelemetry (OTel):</strong> vendor-neutral standard + SDKs for <strong>observability</strong> — generating and collecting <strong>traces, metrics, and logs</strong>. CNCF graduated; merged OpenTracing + OpenCensus.</li></ul><p><em>Exam tip — match the C-I to its domain:</em> CRI = runtime, CNI = networking, CSI = storage, OCI = image/runtime format. OTel = telemetry (the three signals).</p>"}, {"id": "architecture-note-7", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Microservices, the 12-factor app and cloud native design patterns", "title": "Microservices, 12-Factor & Design Patterns", "html": "<p>Cloud native apps favor small, independently deployable services built following 12-factor principles and proven distributed-system patterns.</p><ul><li><strong>Microservices:</strong> small, <strong>loosely coupled</strong>, independently deployable services, each owning one business capability and often its own data store.</li><li><strong>Pros:</strong> independent scaling/deployment, tech diversity, fault isolation. <strong>Cons:</strong> distributed complexity, networking, and observability overhead.</li><li>Contrast with a <strong>monolith</strong> (single deployable unit).</li></ul><ul><li><strong>12-Factor App</strong> — key factors to know: <strong>Config</strong> in the environment (not code), <strong>Backing services</strong> as attached resources, <strong>Processes</strong> are <strong>stateless</strong>, <strong>Port binding</strong>, <strong>Concurrency</strong> via scaling out, <strong>Disposability</strong> (fast startup/graceful shutdown), <strong>Logs</strong> as event streams (to stdout), and strict <strong>dev/prod parity</strong>.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Patterns:</strong> <strong>Sidecar</strong> (helper container in same pod, e.g., proxy/log shipper), <strong>Ambassador</strong> (proxy to external services), <strong>Adapter</strong> (normalize output), <strong>Init container</strong> (run before app starts).</li><li><strong>Service mesh</strong> (Istio, Linkerd) offloads retries, mTLS, and traffic control from app code.</li><li><strong>API Gateway</strong>, <strong>circuit breaker</strong>, and <strong>service discovery</strong> handle resilience and routing.</li></ul><p><em>Exam tips:</em> Stateless + externalized config = easy horizontal scaling. The <strong>Sidecar</strong> pattern is the most-tested; remember containers in a pod share network and storage.</p>"}, {"id": "observability-note-1", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "Observability fundamentals: logs, metrics and traces (the three pillars)", "title": "The Three Pillars of Observability", "html": "<p><strong>Observability</strong> is the ability to understand a system's internal state from its external outputs, enabling you to ask new questions about behavior without shipping new code.</p><ul><li><strong>Monitoring vs observability:</strong> monitoring watches <em>known</em> failure modes (predefined dashboards/alerts); observability helps debug <em>unknown</em> issues by exploring rich telemetry.</li><li><strong>Logs:</strong> timestamped, discrete records of events. Best for detailed, after-the-fact debugging. Can be unstructured (plain text) or <strong>structured</strong> (JSON, easier to query). High volume, high storage cost.</li><li><strong>Metrics:</strong> numeric measurements sampled over time (aggregatable time series). Cheap to store, ideal for dashboards, trends, and <strong>alerting</strong>. Examples: CPU usage, request rate, error count.</li><li><strong>Traces:</strong> follow a single request as it flows across multiple services. A trace is made of <strong>spans</strong> (units of work); answers <em>where</em> latency or failures occur in a distributed call path.</li></ul><h4>Exam tips</h4><ul><li>Know which pillar fits which job: <strong>metrics</strong> = alerting/trends, <strong>logs</strong> = detailed events, <strong>traces</strong> = cross-service request latency.</li><li><strong>OpenTelemetry (OTel)</strong> is the CNCF standard for generating and collecting all three signal types in a vendor-neutral way.</li><li>Containers/pods are <em>ephemeral</em>, so telemetry should be shipped out, not stored locally on the node.</li></ul>"}, {"id": "observability-note-2", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "Prometheus architecture, metric types, exporters, PromQL and Alertmanager", "title": "Prometheus: Metrics, PromQL and Alerting", "html": "<p><strong>Prometheus</strong> is the CNCF graduated monitoring system and the de facto standard for metrics in Kubernetes.</p><ul><li><strong>Pull model:</strong> the Prometheus server <strong>scrapes</strong> metrics over HTTP from targets' <code>/metrics</code> endpoints at intervals; it uses <strong>service discovery</strong> (e.g. Kubernetes API) to find targets dynamically.</li><li><strong>Storage:</strong> a local time-series database (TSDB); data is identified by metric name plus key/value <strong>labels</strong>.</li></ul><h4>Metric types</h4><ul><li><strong>Counter:</strong> monotonically increasing value (e.g. total requests); only goes up or resets to 0.</li><li><strong>Gauge:</strong> value that goes up and down (e.g. memory in use, temperature).</li><li><strong>Histogram:</strong> samples observations into configurable buckets (e.g. request durations); supports quantiles.</li><li><strong>Summary:</strong> like a histogram but calculates quantiles client-side.</li></ul><h4>Components</h4><ul><li><strong>Exporters:</strong> expose metrics from systems that don't natively speak Prometheus (e.g. <code>node_exporter</code> for host metrics, database exporters).</li><li><strong>Pushgateway:</strong> lets short-lived/batch jobs push metrics that Prometheus then scrapes.</li><li><strong>PromQL:</strong> the query language used for dashboards, ad-hoc queries, and alert rules.</li><li><strong>Alertmanager:</strong> a <em>separate</em> component that handles alerts fired by Prometheus rules; it does <strong>deduplication, grouping, silencing, and routing</strong> to receivers (email, Slack, PagerDuty).</li></ul><h4>Exam tips</h4><ul><li>Prometheus <em>evaluates</em> alert rules; <strong>Alertmanager sends the notifications</strong>.</li><li>Grafana is commonly used to <strong>visualize</strong> Prometheus data (Prometheus itself has only a basic UI).</li></ul>"}, {"id": "observability-note-3", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "Distributed tracing with OpenTelemetry and Jaeger", "title": "Distributed Tracing: OpenTelemetry and Jaeger", "html": "<p><strong>Distributed tracing</strong> tracks a request end-to-end across microservices to pinpoint latency and failures in the call path.</p><ul><li><strong>Trace:</strong> the full journey of one request, composed of <strong>spans</strong>.</li><li><strong>Span:</strong> a single named, timed operation (e.g. one service call) with attributes; spans nest into a parent/child tree.</li><li><strong>Context propagation:</strong> a <strong>trace/span ID</strong> is passed between services (via headers like W3C <code>traceparent</code>) so spans link into one trace.</li></ul><h4>OpenTelemetry (OTel)</h4><ul><li>CNCF project (incubating) and the <strong>vendor-neutral standard</strong> for instrumenting and exporting telemetry; covers <strong>traces, metrics, and logs</strong>.</li><li>Provides <strong>SDKs/APIs</strong> for instrumentation (manual and auto) plus the <strong>OpenTelemetry Collector</strong>, which <em>receives, processes, and exports</em> telemetry to many backends.</li><li>Result of merging the older <strong>OpenTracing</strong> and <strong>OpenCensus</strong> projects.</li></ul><h4>Jaeger</h4><ul><li>CNCF graduated project: a <strong>tracing backend</strong> for storing, querying, and <strong>visualizing</strong> traces (Gantt-style waterfall views).</li><li>Originated at Uber; commonly paired with OTel as the data source.</li></ul><h4>Exam tips</h4><ul><li><strong>OTel = generate/collect</strong> telemetry (instrumentation); <strong>Jaeger = store/visualize</strong> traces. They are complementary, not competitors.</li><li><strong>Sampling</strong> reduces trace volume/cost by capturing only a subset of requests.</li></ul>"}, {"id": "observability-note-4", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "Cost management and FinOps in cloud native environments", "title": "Cloud Native Cost Management and FinOps", "html": "<p><strong>FinOps</strong> is a cultural practice and operating model that brings financial accountability to variable cloud spending, with engineering, finance, and business teams collaborating on cost decisions.</p><ul><li><strong>Goal:</strong> maximize business value per dollar, not just minimize cost; balance cost, speed, and quality.</li><li><strong>FinOps Foundation</strong> is hosted by the <strong>Linux Foundation</strong> and defines the practice's principles and phases.</li></ul><h4>Three FinOps phases (lifecycle)</h4><ul><li><strong>Inform:</strong> gain visibility and allocation - show who spends what (tagging, showback/chargeback).</li><li><strong>Optimize:</strong> identify savings - rightsizing, autoscaling, removing idle resources, reserved/spot capacity.</li><li><strong>Operate:</strong> continuously govern and improve cost as part of normal operations.</li></ul><h4>Cloud native cost drivers and levers</h4><ul><li><strong>Autoscaling</strong> matches resources to demand: <strong>HPA</strong> (pod replicas), <strong>VPA</strong> (pod requests/limits), <strong>Cluster Autoscaler / Karpenter</strong> (node count).</li><li><strong>Right-sizing</strong> requests/limits prevents over-provisioning and waste.</li><li><strong>Spot/preemptible instances</strong> cut cost for fault-tolerant workloads.</li><li><strong>Bin packing / efficient scheduling</strong> increases node utilization.</li><li><strong>KubeCost / OpenCost</strong> (CNCF sandbox) provide Kubernetes cost <strong>visibility and allocation</strong> by namespace, deployment, or label.</li></ul><h4>Exam tips</h4><ul><li>Know the three phases: <strong>Inform - Optimize - Operate</strong>.</li><li><strong>OpenCost</strong> is the CNCF spec/tool for measuring Kubernetes spend.</li><li>Pay-as-you-go and elasticity make cloud cost <em>variable</em>, which is exactly why FinOps and tagging/allocation matter.</li></ul>"}], "flashcards": [{"id": "architecture-fc-1", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Cloud native fundamentals and the CNCF landscape", "front": "How does the CNCF define 'cloud native'?", "back": "Cloud native technologies empower organizations to build and run scalable applications in modern, dynamic environments such as public, private, and hybrid clouds. Containers, service meshes, microservices, immutable infrastructure, and declarative APIs exemplify this approach, enabling loosely coupled, resilient, manageable, and observable systems."}, {"id": "architecture-fc-2", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Cloud native fundamentals and the CNCF landscape", "front": "What are the key characteristics (pillars) of cloud native systems?", "back": "Loosely coupled, resilient, manageable, observable, and easily automated. Combined with robust automation, these allow engineers to make high-impact changes frequently and predictably with minimal toil."}, {"id": "architecture-fc-3", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Cloud native fundamentals and the CNCF landscape", "front": "What is the CNCF and what foundation hosts it?", "back": "The Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF), founded in 2015, is a vendor-neutral home for open source cloud native projects. It is part of the Linux Foundation. Kubernetes was its first hosted (seed) project."}, {"id": "architecture-fc-4", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Cloud native fundamentals and the CNCF landscape", "front": "What is 'immutable infrastructure' and why is it central to cloud native?", "back": "Infrastructure (servers/containers) is never modified after deployment; to make a change you replace the component with a new version rather than patching in place. This yields predictable, repeatable, easily rollback-able deployments and avoids configuration drift."}, {"id": "architecture-fc-5", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Autoscaling (Horizontal Pod Autoscaler, Vertical Pod Autoscaler, Cluster Autoscaler)", "front": "What does the Horizontal Pod Autoscaler (HPA) do?", "back": "The HPA automatically scales the number of pod replicas in a workload (Deployment, ReplicaSet, StatefulSet) up or down based on observed metrics such as CPU/memory utilization or custom metrics. It does not apply to non-scalable objects like DaemonSets."}, {"id": "architecture-fc-6", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Autoscaling (Horizontal Pod Autoscaler, Vertical Pod Autoscaler, Cluster Autoscaler)", "front": "What does the Vertical Pod Autoscaler (VPA) do?", "back": "The VPA automatically adjusts the CPU and memory resource requests/limits of pods to match actual usage. Unlike HPA which changes replica count, VPA changes per-pod resources; applying new values typically requires the pod to be recreated."}, {"id": "architecture-fc-7", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Autoscaling (Horizontal Pod Autoscaler, Vertical Pod Autoscaler, Cluster Autoscaler)", "front": "What does the Cluster Autoscaler do, and how does it differ from HPA/VPA?", "back": "The Cluster Autoscaler adjusts the number of nodes in the cluster: it adds nodes when pods are unschedulable (Pending due to insufficient resources) and removes underutilized nodes. HPA/VPA scale pods/resources; Cluster Autoscaler scales the underlying infrastructure."}, {"id": "architecture-fc-8", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Autoscaling (Horizontal Pod Autoscaler, Vertical Pod Autoscaler, Cluster Autoscaler)", "front": "Why should HPA and VPA generally not target the same metric (e.g., CPU) on the same workload?", "back": "They can conflict: HPA scales replica count based on CPU while VPA changes the pod's CPU requests, and each reacting to the other's changes causes thrashing. They can be combined only if driven by different metrics (or VPA in recommendation-only mode)."}, {"id": "architecture-fc-9", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Serverless and Knative / Function-as-a-Service", "front": "What is serverless computing?", "back": "An execution model where the cloud provider dynamically manages server allocation; developers deploy code without provisioning or managing servers. Resources scale automatically with demand (including scale-to-zero) and billing is typically based on actual usage."}, {"id": "architecture-fc-10", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Serverless and Knative / Function-as-a-Service", "front": "What is Knative and what are its two main components?", "back": "Knative is a CNCF project that adds serverless capabilities on top of Kubernetes. Its two components are Knative Serving (request-driven autoscaling including scale-to-zero, revisions, and routing) and Knative Eventing (event-driven architecture with sources, brokers, and triggers)."}, {"id": "architecture-fc-11", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Serverless and Knative / Function-as-a-Service", "front": "What is Function-as-a-Service (FaaS) and how does it relate to serverless?", "back": "FaaS is a serverless model where you deploy individual, event-triggered functions that run on demand and scale automatically. FaaS is a subset of serverless focused on function-level granularity (e.g., AWS Lambda, OpenFaaS, Knative functions)."}, {"id": "architecture-fc-12", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Serverless and Knative / Function-as-a-Service", "front": "What is CloudEvents and why does it matter for serverless?", "back": "CloudEvents is a CNCF specification that defines a common, vendor-neutral format for describing event data. It enables interoperability across serverless platforms, event producers, and consumers (and is used by Knative Eventing)."}, {"id": "architecture-fc-13", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "CNCF community, governance and project maturity levels (Sandbox, Incubating, Graduated)", "front": "What are the three CNCF project maturity levels, in order?", "back": "Sandbox (earliest stage, experimental), Incubating (growing adoption and a healthy community), and Graduated (mature, widely adopted, production-ready). Projects advance based on adoption, governance, and community health, reviewed by the Technical Oversight Committee."}, {"id": "architecture-fc-14", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "CNCF community, governance and project maturity levels (Sandbox, Incubating, Graduated)", "front": "Name several CNCF Graduated projects.", "back": "Examples include Kubernetes, Prometheus, Envoy, containerd, CoreDNS, Fluentd, Helm, Harbor, etcd, Vitess, Jaeger, Linkerd, Open Policy Agent (OPA), and Argo. Graduated status signals maturity and production readiness."}, {"id": "architecture-fc-15", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "CNCF community, governance and project maturity levels (Sandbox, Incubating, Graduated)", "front": "What is the CNCF TOC and what does it do?", "back": "The Technical Oversight Committee (TOC) defines and maintains the technical vision of the CNCF, approves new projects, assigns project maturity levels, oversees the technical landscape, and accepts feedback from end users. It is a key governance body."}, {"id": "architecture-fc-16", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "CNCF community, governance and project maturity levels (Sandbox, Incubating, Graduated)", "front": "What is a CNCF Special Interest Group (SIG) and the role of project maintainers?", "back": "CNCF SIGs are focused groups (e.g., SIG-Security, SIG-Network) of subject-matter experts who help review and guide projects in their domain. Maintainers are responsible for a project's direction, code, and community health."}, {"id": "architecture-fc-17", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Roles and personas in cloud native organizations", "front": "What does an SRE (Site Reliability Engineer) do?", "back": "An SRE applies software engineering practices to operations to keep systems reliable and scalable. They define SLIs/SLOs/SLAs, manage error budgets, automate toil, and handle incident response and on-call. SRE originated at Google."}, {"id": "architecture-fc-18", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Roles and personas in cloud native organizations", "front": "What is DevOps and how does it relate to cloud native?", "back": "DevOps is a culture and set of practices that unite development and operations to deliver software faster and more reliably through automation, CI/CD, and shared responsibility. Cloud native technologies (containers, Kubernetes) are key enablers of DevOps."}, {"id": "architecture-fc-19", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Roles and personas in cloud native organizations", "front": "What do Platform Engineering and a 'platform team' provide?", "back": "Platform engineering builds and maintains an internal developer platform (often atop Kubernetes) that abstracts infrastructure complexity, offering self-service tooling, golden paths, and reusable services so application developers can ship faster with less operational burden."}, {"id": "architecture-fc-20", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Open standards (OCI, CRI, CNI, CSI, SMI, OpenTelemetry)", "front": "What is the OCI (Open Container Initiative) and what specs does it define?", "back": "The OCI is an open governance project (under the Linux Foundation) that standardizes container formats and runtimes. It defines the Runtime Specification (runtime-spec), the Image Specification (image-spec), and the Distribution Specification for registries."}, {"id": "architecture-fc-21", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Open standards (OCI, CRI, CNI, CSI, SMI, OpenTelemetry)", "front": "What is the CRI (Container Runtime Interface)?", "back": "The CRI is the plugin interface (a gRPC API) that lets the kubelet use different container runtimes without recompiling. CRI-compliant runtimes include containerd and CRI-O. (Dockershim was removed in Kubernetes 1.24.)"}, {"id": "architecture-fc-22", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Open standards (OCI, CRI, CNI, CSI, SMI, OpenTelemetry)", "front": "Match the interface to its purpose: CNI, CSI, CRI.", "back": "CRI (Container Runtime Interface) = pluggable container runtimes for the kubelet. CNI (Container Network Interface) = pluggable pod networking (e.g., Calico, Cilium, Flannel). CSI (Container Storage Interface) = pluggable storage/volume drivers from external vendors."}, {"id": "architecture-fc-23", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Open standards (OCI, CRI, CNI, CSI, SMI, OpenTelemetry)", "front": "What is OpenTelemetry (OTel) and which observability signals does it cover?", "back": "OpenTelemetry is a CNCF observability framework providing vendor-neutral APIs, SDKs, and tools to generate, collect, and export telemetry. It covers the three signals: traces, metrics, and logs. It formed from the merger of OpenTracing and OpenCensus."}, {"id": "architecture-fc-24", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Microservices, the 12-factor app and cloud native design patterns", "front": "What is a microservices architecture and how does it contrast with a monolith?", "back": "Microservices structure an application as a collection of small, independently deployable services, each owning a single business capability and communicating over APIs. Unlike a monolith (one large deployable unit), services can be scaled, developed, and deployed independently."}, {"id": "architecture-fc-25", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Microservices, the 12-factor app and cloud native design patterns", "front": "Name several core principles of the Twelve-Factor App methodology.", "back": "Key factors include: one codebase tracked in version control; explicitly declared dependencies; configuration stored in the environment; backing services treated as attached resources; strict separation of build/release/run; stateless processes; port binding; concurrency via the process model; and disposability (fast startup/graceful shutdown)."}, {"id": "observability-fc-1", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "Observability fundamentals: logs, metrics and traces (the three pillars)", "front": "What are the three pillars of observability?", "back": "Logs (discrete, timestamped event records), Metrics (numeric measurements aggregated over time, e.g. CPU or request count), and Traces (the end-to-end path of a single request across services). Together they let you understand a system's internal state from its outputs."}, {"id": "observability-fc-2", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "Observability fundamentals: logs, metrics and traces (the three pillars)", "front": "How does observability differ from monitoring?", "back": "Monitoring tracks known, predefined conditions and alerts when thresholds are crossed ('known unknowns'). Observability lets you ask new questions and explore system behavior you didn't anticipate ('unknown unknowns') by analyzing logs, metrics, and traces."}, {"id": "observability-fc-3", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "Observability fundamentals: logs, metrics and traces (the three pillars)", "front": "What is the difference between a metric and a log?", "back": "A metric is a numeric value sampled over time and is highly aggregatable and cheap to store (e.g. requests_total). A log is a detailed, often textual record of a discrete event, richer in context but more expensive to store and query at scale."}, {"id": "observability-fc-4", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "Observability fundamentals: logs, metrics and traces (the three pillars)", "front": "What is a span in distributed tracing, and how does it relate to a trace?", "back": "A span represents a single unit of work or operation (e.g. one service call) with a start time, duration, and metadata. A trace is the collection of spans, linked by parent-child relationships, that together represent one request's full journey through a system."}, {"id": "observability-fc-5", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "Observability fundamentals: logs, metrics and traces (the three pillars)", "front": "What is cardinality in metrics, and why does it matter?", "back": "Cardinality is the number of unique label/value combinations for a metric (each unique combination is a separate time series). High cardinality (e.g. labeling by user ID) can explode memory and storage in systems like Prometheus, so labels should use bounded, low-cardinality values."}, {"id": "observability-fc-6", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "Prometheus architecture, metric types, exporters, PromQL and Alertmanager", "front": "How does Prometheus collect metrics by default?", "back": "Prometheus uses a pull model: the server periodically scrapes HTTP /metrics endpoints exposed by targets. It stores data in a local time-series database (TSDB). For short-lived jobs that can't be scraped, a Pushgateway is used as an intermediary."}, {"id": "observability-fc-7", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "Prometheus architecture, metric types, exporters, PromQL and Alertmanager", "front": "What are the four core Prometheus metric types?", "back": "Counter (monotonically increasing, e.g. total requests), Gauge (value that can go up or down, e.g. memory usage), Histogram (samples bucketed into configurable ranges plus sum/count), and Summary (client-side calculated quantiles plus sum/count)."}, {"id": "observability-fc-8", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "Prometheus architecture, metric types, exporters, PromQL and Alertmanager", "front": "What is a Prometheus exporter?", "back": "An exporter is a component that translates metrics from a third-party system into the Prometheus exposition format on a /metrics endpoint so Prometheus can scrape them. Examples include node_exporter (host/hardware metrics) and kube-state-metrics (Kubernetes object state)."}, {"id": "observability-fc-9", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "Prometheus architecture, metric types, exporters, PromQL and Alertmanager", "front": "What is the responsibility of Alertmanager versus the Prometheus server?", "back": "The Prometheus server evaluates alerting rules and fires alerts. Alertmanager receives those alerts and handles deduplication, grouping, silencing, inhibition, and routing/notification to receivers like email, Slack, or PagerDuty."}, {"id": "observability-fc-10", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "Prometheus architecture, metric types, exporters, PromQL and Alertmanager", "front": "What is PromQL and what does the rate() function do?", "back": "PromQL (Prometheus Query Language) is the language for selecting and aggregating time-series data. rate() calculates the per-second average rate of increase of a counter over a time range, e.g. rate(http_requests_total[5m])."}, {"id": "observability-fc-11", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "Distributed tracing with OpenTelemetry and Jaeger", "front": "What is OpenTelemetry (OTel)?", "back": "OpenTelemetry is a CNCF project and vendor-neutral set of APIs, SDKs, and tools for generating, collecting, and exporting telemetry data (traces, metrics, and logs). It standardizes instrumentation so data isn't locked to one backend."}, {"id": "observability-fc-12", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "Distributed tracing with OpenTelemetry and Jaeger", "front": "What is the OpenTelemetry Collector and why use it?", "back": "The OTel Collector is a vendor-agnostic proxy that receives, processes (batching, filtering, enrichment), and exports telemetry to one or more backends. It decouples your applications from specific observability vendors and offloads processing from the app."}, {"id": "observability-fc-13", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "Distributed tracing with OpenTelemetry and Jaeger", "front": "What is Jaeger and what is its role relative to OpenTelemetry?", "back": "Jaeger is a CNCF distributed tracing backend used to collect, store, and visualize traces for analysis and root-cause/latency debugging. OpenTelemetry handles instrumentation and data generation; Jaeger is a backend that receives and displays that trace data."}, {"id": "observability-fc-14", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "Distributed tracing with OpenTelemetry and Jaeger", "front": "What is context propagation in distributed tracing?", "back": "Context propagation passes trace identifiers (trace ID and span ID) across service boundaries, typically via HTTP headers, so spans from different services can be correlated into a single trace. The W3C Trace Context standard defines the traceparent header for this."}, {"id": "observability-fc-15", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "Distributed tracing with OpenTelemetry and Jaeger", "front": "What is trace sampling and why is it used?", "back": "Sampling decides which traces to record and export rather than keeping every trace, controlling cost and overhead. Head-based sampling decides at the trace's start, while tail-based sampling decides after the full trace is seen (e.g. keep all errors/slow requests)."}, {"id": "observability-fc-16", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "Cost management and FinOps in cloud native environments", "front": "What is FinOps?", "back": "FinOps (Cloud Financial Operations) is a cultural practice and framework bringing financial accountability to variable cloud spend. It unites finance, engineering, and business teams to make data-driven, real-time decisions balancing cost, speed, and quality; it is governed by the FinOps Foundation under the Linux Foundation."}, {"id": "observability-fc-17", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "Cost management and FinOps in cloud native environments", "front": "What are the three phases of the FinOps lifecycle?", "back": "Inform (gain visibility, allocation, and benchmarking of cloud costs), Optimize (identify and act on savings such as rightsizing and reserved capacity), and Operate (continuously govern and align spend with business goals through ongoing processes)."}, {"id": "observability-fc-18", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "Cost management and FinOps in cloud native environments", "front": "What is OpenCost and what problem does it solve?", "back": "OpenCost is a CNCF project that provides a vendor-neutral, open-source specification and tool for measuring and allocating Kubernetes cloud costs in real time, broken down by namespace, deployment, pod, or label. It addresses cost visibility/allocation in shared clusters."}, {"id": "observability-fc-19", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "Cost management and FinOps in cloud native environments", "front": "Why is resource rightsizing important for cloud native cost management?", "back": "Setting accurate Kubernetes requests/limits prevents over-provisioning (paying for idle capacity) and under-provisioning (throttling and OOM kills). Rightsizing based on actual usage, aided by tools like the Vertical Pod Autoscaler, improves bin-packing efficiency and reduces wasted spend."}], "questions": [{"id": "architecture-q-1", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Cloud Native Fundamentals", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "According to the CNCF's definition, which set of characteristics best describes cloud native technologies?", "options": ["Running applications exclusively on a single public cloud provider to maximize vendor-specific features", "Building and running scalable applications in modern, dynamic environments such as public, private, and hybrid clouds using approaches like containers, microservices, and declarative APIs", "Migrating monolithic applications onto virtual machines without changing their architecture", "Eliminating all automation in favor of manually managed, long-lived servers for predictability"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "The CNCF defines cloud native as building and running scalable applications in modern, dynamic environments using technologies like containers, service meshes, microservices, immutable infrastructure, and declarative APIs. The other options contradict core cloud native principles such as portability and automation."}, {"id": "architecture-q-2", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "CNCF Landscape", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "Which organization hosts Kubernetes and serves as the vendor-neutral home for many cloud native open source projects?", "options": ["The Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF)", "The Apache Software Foundation (ASF)", "The Open Container Initiative (OCI)", "The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF)"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "The CNCF, part of the Linux Foundation, hosts Kubernetes and many other cloud native projects. The OCI defines container image and runtime standards but does not host Kubernetes, and the ASF and IETF are separate foundations with different scopes."}, {"id": "architecture-q-3", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "CNCF Project Maturity", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "What is the correct order of the CNCF project maturity levels, from least to most mature?", "options": ["Incubating, Sandbox, Graduated", "Sandbox, Incubating, Graduated", "Graduated, Incubating, Sandbox", "Sandbox, Graduated, Incubating"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "CNCF projects progress through three maturity levels: Sandbox (earliest stage), then Incubating, then Graduated (most mature, indicating broad adoption and production readiness). Kubernetes and Prometheus are examples of Graduated projects."}, {"id": "architecture-q-4", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Cloud Native Fundamentals", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "Which statement best explains the difference between containers and traditional virtual machines (VMs)?", "options": ["Containers each include a full guest operating system, while VMs share the host kernel", "Containers share the host operating system kernel and isolate the application, while each VM runs its own full guest operating system on a hypervisor", "VMs are always more lightweight and start faster than containers", "Containers can only run on bare metal, whereas VMs can run in the cloud"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "Containers virtualize at the OS level, sharing the host kernel and packaging just the application and its dependencies, which makes them lighter and faster to start than VMs. VMs run a full guest OS on a hypervisor, so the description in option B is correct while the others reverse or distort these facts."}, {"id": "architecture-q-5", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "CNCF Landscape", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "A team needs an observability tool for metrics-based monitoring and alerting. Which CNCF Graduated project is purpose-built for collecting time-series metrics and is most commonly paired with Kubernetes for this need?", "options": ["Envoy", "Prometheus", "Helm", "containerd"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "Prometheus is a CNCF Graduated project designed for time-series metrics collection, querying (PromQL), and alerting. Envoy is a service proxy, Helm is a package manager for Kubernetes, and containerd is a container runtime, so none of those address metrics monitoring."}, {"id": "architecture-q-6", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Cloud Native Principles", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "In the context of cloud native design, what does the principle of 'immutable infrastructure' mean?", "options": ["Servers and components are never replaced, so they must be patched in place to remain available", "Once deployed, infrastructure components are not modified in place; instead, changes are made by replacing them with new, freshly built instances", "Infrastructure configuration is stored only in a database and can be edited live without redeployment", "Application code cannot be changed after the first release without recompiling the kernel"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "Immutable infrastructure means deployed components are never changed in place; to apply changes you build and deploy a new instance and replace the old one, which improves consistency and reproducibility. Option A describes the opposite (mutable, in-place patching) approach."}, {"id": "architecture-q-7", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Autoscaling", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "What does the Horizontal Pod Autoscaler (HPA) adjust in response to observed load?", "options": ["The number of pod replicas for a workload", "The CPU and memory requests/limits of each pod", "The number of nodes in the cluster", "The container image version of the workload"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "The HPA scales horizontally by increasing or decreasing the number of pod replicas in a workload (e.g., a Deployment or StatefulSet). Changing per-pod resource requests/limits is the job of the Vertical Pod Autoscaler, and changing node count is the Cluster Autoscaler."}, {"id": "architecture-q-8", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Autoscaling", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "Which autoscaler is responsible for adding or removing worker nodes from a cluster when pods cannot be scheduled or nodes are underutilized?", "options": ["Cluster Autoscaler", "Horizontal Pod Autoscaler", "Vertical Pod Autoscaler", "kube-scheduler"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "The Cluster Autoscaler operates at the infrastructure level, adding nodes when pods are Pending due to insufficient resources and removing underutilized nodes whose pods can be rescheduled elsewhere. The kube-scheduler only places pods on existing nodes; it does not provision new ones."}, {"id": "architecture-q-9", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Autoscaling", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "What is the primary function of the Vertical Pod Autoscaler (VPA)?", "options": ["Recommending or adjusting CPU and memory resource requests for pods", "Increasing the replica count of a Deployment", "Provisioning additional nodes for the cluster", "Distributing pods evenly across availability zones"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "The VPA right-sizes individual pods by recommending or setting their CPU and memory requests based on observed usage. Adjusting replica counts is the HPA's role, and provisioning nodes is the Cluster Autoscaler's role."}, {"id": "architecture-q-10", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Autoscaling", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "By default, what metric does a basic Horizontal Pod Autoscaler use to decide when to scale a workload?", "options": ["Average CPU utilization relative to the pods' resource requests", "The number of pending pods in the scheduler queue", "Total node disk usage across the cluster", "The container restart count"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "A basic HPA scales based on average CPU utilization measured as a percentage of the pods' CPU requests, sourced from the Metrics Server. This is why defining CPU resource requests is essential for the HPA to function. Pending-pod counts drive the Cluster Autoscaler instead."}, {"id": "architecture-q-11", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Autoscaling", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "Why is running the Vertical Pod Autoscaler and the Horizontal Pod Autoscaler on the same workload using the same resource metric (such as CPU) generally discouraged?", "options": ["They can conflict because both react to the same metric, leading to unstable or competing scaling decisions", "The VPA disables the Metrics Server, which the HPA depends on", "Kubernetes refuses to install both controllers in the same cluster", "The HPA can only act on memory while the VPA can only act on CPU"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "When both autoscalers act on the same resource metric, they can fight each other: the HPA adds replicas to reduce per-pod CPU while the VPA simultaneously resizes the pods' requests, producing unstable behavior. They can be combined safely when driven by different metrics, or by running VPA in recommendation-only mode. Both controllers can coexist in a cluster; the concern is using them on the same workload and metric."}, {"id": "architecture-q-12", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Autoscaling", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "A workload's CPU-based HPA is configured but never scales out even though the application is clearly overloaded. Which condition is the most likely root cause?", "options": ["The pods have no CPU resource requests defined, so the HPA cannot compute utilization", "The cluster has more nodes available than the workload needs", "The Deployment has more than three replicas", "The pods are exposed through a LoadBalancer Service"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "A CPU-based HPA computes utilization as a percentage of the pods' CPU requests; if no requests are defined, it has no baseline and reports an unknown metric, so it cannot calculate utilization or trigger scaling. The Service type, current replica count, and number of available nodes do not prevent the HPA from evaluating its metric."}, {"id": "architecture-q-13", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Serverless / Knative", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "Which of the following is a defining characteristic of the serverless computing model?", "options": ["Developers must provision and patch the underlying virtual machines before deploying code", "The cloud provider or platform dynamically manages the allocation of compute resources, and the application can scale to zero when idle", "Applications run as long-lived StatefulSets that always keep at least three replicas running", "Code is compiled once and can never be scaled horizontally"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "Serverless abstracts away server management; the platform handles resource allocation and can scale workloads up and down, including down to zero when there is no traffic. The other options describe traditional infrastructure or contradict the elastic, scale-to-zero nature of serverless."}, {"id": "architecture-q-14", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Knative", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "Knative is best described as which of the following?", "options": ["A container runtime that replaces containerd for running serverless functions", "A CNCF project providing components for deploying, running, and managing serverless and event-driven applications on Kubernetes", "A standalone Function-as-a-Service product that runs independently of Kubernetes", "A service mesh that replaces Istio for all cluster traffic"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "Knative is a CNCF project that adds serverless and event-driven capabilities on top of Kubernetes. It is not a container runtime, is not independent of Kubernetes, and is not itself a service mesh (though it can integrate with one)."}, {"id": "architecture-q-15", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Knative components", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "Knative is primarily organized into which two functional areas?", "options": ["Serving and Eventing", "Ingress and Egress", "Build and Deploy", "Scheduler and Controller"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Knative consists of Serving (which manages request-driven, autoscaling workloads, including scale-to-zero) and Eventing (which provides infrastructure for consuming and producing events). The former Build component was deprecated and evolved into the separate Tekton project."}, {"id": "architecture-q-16", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Knative Serving / autoscaling", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "A key capability of Knative Serving that distinguishes it from a standard Kubernetes Deployment is that it can:", "options": ["Run containers without any container image", "Automatically scale a workload down to zero replicas when there is no traffic and scale it back up on demand", "Guarantee that pods are never rescheduled to another node", "Bypass the Kubernetes API server for faster networking"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "Knative Serving provides request-driven autoscaling that includes scaling to zero when idle and rapidly scaling back up when requests arrive, which a plain Deployment does not do natively. The other options are inaccurate descriptions of Knative."}, {"id": "architecture-q-17", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Knative Eventing", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "In Knative Eventing, which statement best describes the role of a Broker and Trigger?", "options": ["A Broker stores container images while a Trigger compiles source code into functions", "A Broker receives events and a Trigger defines filtering rules that route matching events to a subscriber", "A Broker enforces network policies while a Trigger schedules pods onto nodes", "A Broker is a load balancer for HTTP traffic and a Trigger is a horizontal pod autoscaler"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "In Knative Eventing, a Broker provides an event mesh/ingress point that receives events, and a Trigger subscribes to that Broker with filter criteria, routing matching events to a target subscriber. The other options confuse eventing with unrelated build, networking, or scheduling functions."}, {"id": "architecture-q-18", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Serverless / CloudEvents", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "Knative Eventing adopts which CNCF specification to provide a common, vendor-neutral format for describing event data across systems?", "options": ["OpenTelemetry", "CloudEvents", "Open Policy Agent (OPA)", "Service Mesh Interface (SMI)"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "CloudEvents is a CNCF specification that standardizes the format and metadata of events, and Knative Eventing uses it for interoperable event delivery. OpenTelemetry addresses observability/telemetry, OPA handles policy, and SMI defines a service mesh interface."}, {"id": "architecture-q-19", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "CNCF Project Maturity", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "What are the three project maturity levels used by the CNCF, in order from least to most mature?", "options": ["Alpha, Beta, Stable", "Sandbox, Incubating, Graduated", "Proposed, Adopted, Archived", "Experimental, Production, Retired"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "The CNCF maturity model has exactly three levels: Sandbox (earliest stage), Incubating (growing adoption), and Graduated (mature, widely adopted). Alpha/Beta/Stable describe Kubernetes API/feature stages, not CNCF project maturity."}, {"id": "architecture-q-20", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "CNCF Governance", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "Which CNCF body is primarily responsible for defining and maintaining the technical vision and overseeing projects, including approving moves between maturity levels?", "options": ["The Governing Board (GB)", "The Technical Oversight Committee (TOC)", "The End User Community", "The CNCF Marketing Committee"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "The Technical Oversight Committee (TOC) defines the technical vision and votes on project acceptance and promotions between maturity levels. The Governing Board handles budget, marketing, and business oversight rather than technical project decisions."}, {"id": "architecture-q-21", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "CNCF Project Maturity", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "A project has achieved very high adoption, has committers from multiple organizations, a documented and independent governance process, and has completed an independent security audit. Which CNCF maturity level does this best describe?", "options": ["Sandbox", "Incubating", "Graduated", "Archived"], "answerIndex": 2, "explanation": "Graduated projects must demonstrate widespread adoption, a healthy multi-organization committer base, defined governance, and a completed independent third-party security audit. Incubating projects show production use but have not yet met all of the stricter Graduated criteria."}, {"id": "architecture-q-22", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "CNCF Project Maturity", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "What is the main purpose of the CNCF Sandbox level?", "options": ["To host only projects that are already production-ready and widely deployed", "To provide a neutral home for early-stage, innovative projects to encourage experimentation and growth", "To archive projects that are no longer actively maintained", "To certify that a project has passed an independent security audit"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "Sandbox is the entry point for early-stage projects, giving them a vendor-neutral home and encouraging public collaboration and experimentation. Production readiness and security audits are expectations associated with the later Incubating and Graduated levels, not Sandbox."}, {"id": "architecture-q-23", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "CNCF Foundation Structure", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "The CNCF operates as part of which larger umbrella foundation?", "options": ["The Apache Software Foundation", "The Linux Foundation", "The Open Source Initiative (OSI)", "The Eclipse Foundation"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "The CNCF is a project hosted under the Linux Foundation, which provides the legal and organizational umbrella. The Apache Software Foundation, OSI, and Eclipse Foundation are separate organizations not responsible for CNCF governance."}, {"id": "architecture-q-24", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "CNCF Project Maturity", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "Kubernetes was the first project to be accepted by the CNCF and later reached the highest maturity level. Which statement is accurate about Kubernetes' status within the CNCF?", "options": ["Kubernetes remains at the Incubating level because of its large scope", "Kubernetes is a Graduated CNCF project", "Kubernetes is hosted in the CNCF Sandbox pending an audit", "Kubernetes was archived after its 1.0 release and is maintained independently"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "Kubernetes is a Graduated CNCF project (graduated in March 2018), having met the criteria for widespread adoption, diverse governance, and security maturity. It is not Incubating, Sandbox, or archived; archived status is reserved for projects no longer under active development."}, {"id": "architecture-q-25", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Cloud Native Architecture: Roles & Personas", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "Which role is primarily responsible for bridging development and operations by automating the build, test, and deployment pipeline to enable faster, more reliable software delivery?", "options": ["DevOps engineer", "Database administrator", "Security auditor", "Product manager"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "A DevOps engineer focuses on collaboration between development and operations and on automating CI/CD pipelines to speed up reliable delivery. A database administrator manages data stores, and a product manager defines product direction rather than delivery automation."}, {"id": "architecture-q-26", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Cloud Native Architecture: Roles & Personas", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "In cloud native organizations, what is the main responsibility of a Site Reliability Engineer (SRE)?", "options": ["Applying software engineering practices to operations in order to keep services reliable and meet defined SLOs", "Designing the marketing strategy for cloud products", "Writing only frontend user interface code", "Negotiating vendor contracts for cloud spend"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "SRE applies software engineering to operational problems, using error budgets and SLOs to balance reliability with feature velocity. The other options describe marketing, frontend development, and procurement, none of which is the SRE's core mandate."}, {"id": "architecture-q-27", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Cloud Native Architecture: Roles & Personas", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "A platform engineering team builds an internal developer platform on top of Kubernetes. What is the primary goal of this team?", "options": ["To provide self-service tooling and golden paths that reduce cognitive load for application developers", "To manually approve every pull request submitted by developers", "To replace application developers by writing all business logic themselves", "To exclusively manage end-user customer support tickets"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Platform engineering builds an internal developer platform offering self-service capabilities and golden paths so application teams can ship faster with less operational overhead. It does not replace developers or own customer support, and gatekeeping every PR contradicts the self-service goal."}, {"id": "architecture-q-28", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Cloud Native Architecture: Roles & Personas", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "Which persona is MOST directly concerned with consuming a Kubernetes platform to deploy and run their applications, rather than operating the cluster control plane itself?", "options": ["Application developer", "Cluster administrator", "Network operations center technician", "Hardware procurement specialist"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Application developers are platform consumers who package and deploy workloads, while the cluster administrator is responsible for operating and maintaining the cluster and its control plane. The other roles are not the typical consumers of the application-deployment workflow."}, {"id": "architecture-q-29", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Cloud Native Architecture: Roles & Personas", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "An organization adopts a 'you build it, you run it' model. What organizational and cultural shift does this most directly represent?", "options": ["Development teams take on operational ownership of their services in production, including on-call responsibility", "A central operations team takes exclusive ownership of all production incidents away from developers", "Developers are prohibited from accessing any production telemetry or logs", "All deployments must be performed manually by a release management board"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "'You build it, you run it' decentralizes operational ownership so the team that develops a service also operates it in production, often including on-call. This is the opposite of handing all operations to a separate central team or imposing manual release boards."}, {"id": "architecture-q-30", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Cloud Native Architecture: Roles & Personas", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "Within the cloud native security community, which approach best reflects how the 'DevSecOps' persona integrates security into delivery?", "options": ["Shifting security left by embedding automated security checks and shared responsibility throughout the CI/CD pipeline", "Deferring all security reviews to a single manual gate immediately before production release", "Outsourcing security entirely to the cloud provider under the shared responsibility model", "Restricting security concerns to the network firewall configuration only"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "DevSecOps 'shifts security left,' embedding automated checks and shared ownership of security across the whole pipeline rather than treating it as a final manual gate. A single pre-release gate or firewall-only scope contradicts the continuous, integrated model, and the cloud shared responsibility model never fully outsources application security."}, {"id": "architecture-q-31", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Open Standards: CRI", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "Which open standard defines the interface that allows the kubelet to use different container runtimes (such as containerd or CRI-O) without being recompiled?", "options": ["Container Runtime Interface (CRI)", "Container Network Interface (CNI)", "Open Container Initiative (OCI)", "Container Storage Interface (CSI)"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "The CRI is the gRPC-based API the kubelet uses to talk to container runtimes, decoupling Kubernetes from any specific runtime. CNI handles networking and CSI handles storage, so neither concerns runtime communication."}, {"id": "architecture-q-32", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Open Standards: OCI", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "The Open Container Initiative (OCI) primarily standardizes which of the following?", "options": ["How container images are built, formatted, and run at runtime", "How pods are scheduled onto nodes in a cluster", "How services discover one another across a service mesh", "How telemetry data is collected and exported from applications"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "OCI publishes the image, runtime, and distribution specifications that define a portable container image format and runtime behavior. Scheduling is a Kubernetes concern, service discovery relates to service meshes/SMI, and telemetry is OpenTelemetry's domain."}, {"id": "architecture-q-33", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Open Standards: CSI", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "A storage vendor wants their block storage product to work with Kubernetes, Nomad, and other orchestrators without writing code inside each orchestrator's core. Which standard should they implement?", "options": ["Container Storage Interface (CSI)", "Container Runtime Interface (CRI)", "Open Container Initiative (OCI)", "Service Mesh Interface (SMI)"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "CSI is the standard interface that lets storage providers write a single driver that any supporting orchestrator can use, removing the need for in-tree (core) storage code. CRI is for runtimes, OCI is for image/runtime format, and SMI is for service meshes."}, {"id": "architecture-q-34", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Open Standards: OpenTelemetry", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "Which statement best describes the purpose of OpenTelemetry in a cloud native environment?", "options": ["It provides a vendor-neutral set of APIs, SDKs, and tools to generate and collect telemetry such as traces, metrics, and logs", "It provides a standard plugin interface for attaching network interfaces to pods", "It defines the on-disk format of container images for portability", "It enforces traffic policies and mutual TLS between services in a mesh"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "OpenTelemetry is a CNCF observability framework offering vendor-neutral APIs, SDKs, and collectors for traces, metrics, and logs. Networking plugins are CNI, image format is OCI, and mesh traffic policy is handled by service mesh tooling."}, {"id": "architecture-q-35", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Open Standards: SMI", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "The Service Mesh Interface (SMI) was created mainly to address which problem?", "options": ["Providing a standard set of Kubernetes APIs so workloads and tools can work across different service mesh implementations", "Defining a common gRPC API for kubelets to manage container lifecycles", "Standardizing how persistent volumes are provisioned by storage vendors", "Specifying a portable image format that runtimes must be able to execute"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "SMI defined a common, mesh-agnostic set of Kubernetes CRDs (for traffic policy, telemetry, and access control) so tooling could be portable across meshes like Istio, Linkerd, and Consul. The other options describe CRI, CSI, and OCI respectively."}, {"id": "architecture-q-36", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Open Standards: CNI", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "When a pod is created on a node, which component is responsible for invoking a CNI plugin to set up the pod's network connectivity?", "options": ["The container runtime, on behalf of the kubelet, calls the CNI plugin to configure the pod's network", "The kube-scheduler directly calls the CNI plugin once the pod is bound to a node", "The API server calls the CNI plugin when the pod object is first persisted to etcd", "kube-proxy calls the CNI plugin to assign the pod its IP address"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "The kubelet instructs the container runtime, which invokes the configured CNI plugin to wire up the pod's network namespace and assign an IP. The scheduler only binds pods to nodes, the API server persists state, and kube-proxy manages Service routing rules, not per-pod CNI setup."}, {"id": "architecture-q-37", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Microservices Architecture", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "Which characteristic best distinguishes a microservices architecture from a traditional monolithic application?", "options": ["All business logic is compiled into a single deployable artifact that scales as one unit", "The application is decomposed into small, independently deployable services organized around business capabilities", "Each service must be written in the same programming language to ensure compatibility", "Services share a single database schema to guarantee data consistency"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "Microservices decompose an application into small, loosely coupled services that can be developed, deployed, and scaled independently, each owning a business capability. A single deployable artifact describes a monolith, and microservices typically allow polyglot implementations and favor a database-per-service rather than a shared schema."}, {"id": "architecture-q-38", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "12-Factor App", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "According to the 12-factor app methodology, how should application configuration that varies between deploys (such as database URLs and credentials) be supplied?", "options": ["Hardcoded as constants in the application source code", "Stored in the environment (e.g., environment variables) and kept separate from code", "Committed to the same version control repository as the code in a config file", "Embedded directly into the container image at build time for every environment"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "Factor III (Config) requires strict separation of config from code, storing deploy-varying values in the environment so the same build can run across environments without code changes. Hardcoding, committing secrets to source control, or baking environment-specific values into the image all violate this principle."}, {"id": "architecture-q-39", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "12-Factor App", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "A cloud native application stores user session state in the memory of each running container. When the application is scaled horizontally and requests are load balanced, users are intermittently logged out. Which 12-factor principle is being violated?", "options": ["Processes should be stateless and share-nothing, persisting state in a backing service", "Build, release, and run stages should be strictly separated", "Logs should be treated as event streams written to stdout", "Dev/prod parity should be maintained to keep environments similar"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Factor VI (Processes) states that processes must be stateless and share-nothing; any persistent state belongs in a stateful backing service such as a database or cache. Keeping session state in container memory breaks horizontal scalability because requests routed to a different replica lose that in-memory state."}, {"id": "architecture-q-40", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Cloud Native Design Patterns", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "In Kubernetes, which design pattern places a helper container alongside the main application container in the same Pod so it can extend or enhance the main container (for example, by shipping its logs or syncing content) while sharing the Pod's network and volumes?", "options": ["Singleton pattern", "Sidecar pattern", "Strangler fig pattern", "Circuit breaker pattern"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "The sidecar pattern adds a secondary container to a Pod to augment the primary container, leveraging the shared network namespace and volumes (common for logging, proxying, or content sync). The circuit breaker and strangler fig are resilience and migration patterns, and singleton is a general object-creation pattern, not a Pod composition pattern."}, {"id": "architecture-q-41", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Cloud Native Design Patterns", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "Which design pattern improves the resilience of microservices by stopping calls to a downstream service that is failing, allowing it time to recover and preventing cascading failures across the system?", "options": ["Service discovery pattern", "Circuit breaker pattern", "Sidecar pattern", "Leader election pattern"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "The circuit breaker pattern detects repeated failures and 'opens' to short-circuit further requests to the failing dependency, protecting the caller and giving the dependency time to recover, thereby preventing cascading failures. Service discovery handles locating services, and the sidecar pattern is about Pod-level container composition."}, {"id": "architecture-q-42", "domainId": "architecture", "topic": "Microservices & Migration Patterns", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "An organization wants to incrementally migrate functionality out of a large legacy monolith into new microservices, gradually intercepting and rerouting requests to the new services until the monolith can be retired. Which pattern describes this approach?", "options": ["Strangler fig pattern", "Ambassador pattern", "Bulkhead pattern", "Saga pattern"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "The strangler fig pattern incrementally replaces a monolith by routing specific functionality to new services over time until the legacy system is fully retired, reducing the risk of a 'big bang' rewrite. The bulkhead pattern isolates resources for fault containment, the ambassador pattern proxies outbound connections, and the saga pattern manages distributed transactions."}, {"id": "observability-q-1", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "Three Pillars of Observability", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "Cloud native observability is commonly described in terms of three pillars. Which set correctly names these three pillars?", "options": ["Logs, metrics, and traces", "Alerts, dashboards, and reports", "Pods, services, and deployments", "CPU, memory, and disk"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "The three pillars of observability are logs, metrics, and traces. Alerts and dashboards are downstream uses of this telemetry, not the pillars themselves, and the other options describe Kubernetes objects or resource types rather than telemetry signals."}, {"id": "observability-q-2", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "Metrics", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "Which description best characterizes a 'metric' as a telemetry signal?", "options": ["A numeric measurement sampled or aggregated over time, such as request count or CPU usage", "A free-form text record describing a single discrete event", "The end-to-end path of a single request as it moves across services", "A snapshot of all configuration applied to a cluster"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Metrics are numeric measurements captured over time (counters, gauges, histograms), which makes them efficient to store and well suited to trending and alerting. A free-form text record describes a log, and an end-to-end request path describes a trace."}, {"id": "observability-q-3", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "Distributed Tracing", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "A request enters a frontend service, which then calls an authentication service and a database service before responding. Which observability signal is specifically designed to show how this single request flows across all of these services and where time is spent?", "options": ["Distributed traces", "Counter metrics", "Container logs", "Liveness probes"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Distributed tracing follows a single request across service boundaries and breaks it into spans, revealing latency and the call path through the system. Metrics aggregate numbers, logs capture discrete events per component, and liveness probes are a Kubernetes health-check mechanism, not a telemetry signal."}, {"id": "observability-q-4", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "Logs", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "Which statement most accurately describes logs compared to metrics in a cloud native system?", "options": ["Logs are discrete, timestamped event records (often text or structured fields), useful for detailed context about what happened", "Logs are pre-aggregated numeric time series optimized for low-cardinality storage", "Logs always require a tracing context ID to be useful", "Logs can only be produced by the Kubernetes control plane, not by applications"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Logs are discrete, timestamped event records (plain text or structured) that provide rich context about specific events. Pre-aggregated numeric time series describe metrics; logs do not require trace IDs, and any application or component can emit logs, not just the control plane."}, {"id": "observability-q-5", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "Traces and Spans", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "In distributed tracing, what is the relationship between a 'trace' and a 'span'?", "options": ["A trace represents the full journey of one request and is composed of one or more spans, each representing a unit of work", "A span represents the full request journey and is composed of multiple traces", "A trace and a span are interchangeable terms for the same single measurement", "A span is a numeric counter while a trace is a log line"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "A trace is the end-to-end record of a single request and is made up of spans, where each span represents an individual operation or unit of work (such as one service call) with its own timing. The relationship is not reversed, the terms are not interchangeable, and spans are not counters."}, {"id": "observability-q-6", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "Signals and Tooling", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "A team wants to set up alerting that fires when the rate of HTTP 500 responses across a service exceeds a threshold over the last 5 minutes. Which telemetry signal is the most natural fit for driving this alert, and which CNCF project is most associated with collecting and querying it?", "options": ["Metrics, collected and queried with Prometheus", "Traces, collected and queried with Prometheus", "Logs, collected and queried with Jaeger", "Metrics, collected and queried with Jaeger"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Threshold-based alerting on a rate over a time window is naturally expressed with metrics (numeric time series), and Prometheus is the CNCF project commonly used to collect, store, and query metrics for alerting. Jaeger is a tracing backend, not a metrics or alerting engine."}, {"id": "observability-q-7", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "Prometheus Architecture", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "Which statement best describes how the Prometheus server collects metrics from a target application by default?", "options": ["The application pushes metrics to the Prometheus server over a persistent gRPC stream", "The Prometheus server pulls (scrapes) metrics by making HTTP requests to the target's metrics endpoint", "The Prometheus server queries the application's database directly for stored metrics", "A sidecar agent forwards all metrics to Prometheus via a message queue"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "Prometheus uses a pull-based model: it periodically scrapes targets over HTTP, typically at a /metrics endpoint. Pushing is the exception (via the Pushgateway for short-lived jobs), and Prometheus does not read application databases directly."}, {"id": "observability-q-8", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "Prometheus Metric Types", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "An application tracks the total number of HTTP requests it has served since startup, a value that only ever increases (and resets to zero on restart). Which Prometheus metric type is most appropriate?", "options": ["Gauge", "Counter", "Histogram", "Summary"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "A counter is a cumulative metric that only increases (or resets to zero on restart), making it ideal for totals like request counts. A gauge is for values that go up and down, while histograms and summaries are used to observe distributions such as request durations."}, {"id": "observability-q-9", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "Prometheus Exporters", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "You want Prometheus to collect CPU, memory, disk, and network metrics about the Linux host operating system running a Kubernetes node. Which component is the standard choice for exposing these OS-level metrics?", "options": ["kube-state-metrics", "Node Exporter", "Alertmanager", "Pushgateway"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "Node Exporter exposes hardware and OS-level metrics (CPU, memory, disk, network) for *nix hosts. kube-state-metrics instead exposes the state of Kubernetes API objects (Deployments, Pods, etc.), not host resource metrics."}, {"id": "observability-q-10", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "PromQL", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "Why is the rate() function commonly used when querying a Prometheus counter such as http_requests_total, rather than reading the counter's raw value?", "options": ["rate() converts the counter into a gauge so it can be averaged across instances", "rate() calculates the per-second average increase of the counter over a time range, which is more meaningful than a continuously growing total", "rate() is required because counters cannot be displayed on a graph without it", "rate() resets the counter to zero so the next scrape starts fresh"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "rate() computes the per-second average rate of increase of a counter over a given time window and automatically accounts for counter resets, giving a useful metric like requests per second. The raw counter value just keeps growing and is rarely useful on its own; rate() does not mutate the underlying counter."}, {"id": "observability-q-11", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "Alertmanager", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "In a typical Prometheus monitoring stack, what is the primary responsibility of Alertmanager?", "options": ["Evaluating alerting rules against scraped metrics to decide when alerts fire", "Scraping additional targets that the Prometheus server cannot reach", "Handling alerts sent by Prometheus, including deduplication, grouping, silencing, and routing them to receivers like email or Slack", "Long-term storage and downsampling of historical metric data"], "answerIndex": 2, "explanation": "Alertmanager receives alerts that the Prometheus server has already fired, then deduplicates, groups, silences, and routes them to notification receivers. The evaluation of alerting rules is done by the Prometheus server itself, not by Alertmanager."}, {"id": "observability-q-12", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "PromQL", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "A Prometheus instance scrapes the same job from three replicas, producing the series http_requests_total with a unique 'instance' label per replica. Which PromQL expression returns the combined per-second request rate across all three replicas as a single value?", "options": ["rate(http_requests_total[5m])", "sum(rate(http_requests_total[5m]))", "rate(sum(http_requests_total)[5m])", "avg(http_requests_total[5m])"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "You must compute rate() per series first (so counter resets are handled correctly), then aggregate with sum() to collapse the per-instance results into one combined rate. sum(rate(...)) does exactly this; applying sum() before rate() is invalid because rate() needs a range vector of individual counter series."}, {"id": "observability-q-13", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "Distributed Tracing", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "In distributed tracing, what does a single \"span\" represent?", "options": ["A single named, timed unit of work within a request, such as one service call or database query", "The complete end-to-end journey of a request across all services", "A numeric metric value sampled at a fixed interval", "A log line emitted by an application container"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "A span is the basic building block of a trace: one named operation with a start time and duration. The complete end-to-end journey of a request is the trace, which is a tree (or DAG) of spans, so that distractor describes a trace rather than a span."}, {"id": "observability-q-14", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "OpenTelemetry", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "Which CNCF project provides a vendor-neutral set of APIs, SDKs, and tools for generating and collecting traces, metrics, and logs?", "options": ["OpenTelemetry", "Jaeger", "Prometheus", "Fluentd"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "OpenTelemetry (OTel) is the CNCF project that standardizes instrumentation and telemetry collection across all three signals. Jaeger is a tracing backend for storage and visualization, while Prometheus and Fluentd focus on metrics and logs respectively rather than providing the unified instrumentation standard."}, {"id": "observability-q-15", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "Tracing Backends", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "What is the primary role of Jaeger in an observability stack?", "options": ["Storing, querying, and visualizing distributed traces", "Scraping and storing time-series metrics from targets", "Auto-instrumenting application code without any libraries", "Forwarding container logs to long-term object storage"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Jaeger is a distributed tracing backend used to collect, store, and visualize traces, including a UI for inspecting request flows and latency. Scraping time-series metrics is Prometheus's job, and log forwarding is handled by tools like Fluentd or Fluent Bit."}, {"id": "observability-q-16", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "Trace Context Propagation", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "How does a trace stay connected as a request passes from one microservice to the next?", "options": ["Trace context (such as the trace ID) is propagated, typically via HTTP headers following the W3C Trace Context standard", "Each service independently generates a new trace ID that the backend later correlates by timestamp", "The Kubernetes API server injects the trace ID into every pod's environment variables", "A shared persistent volume stores the trace ID for all services to read"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Context propagation passes identifiers like the trace ID and parent span ID between services, commonly through HTTP headers using the W3C Trace Context (traceparent) standard, so spans from different services join one trace. Generating independent IDs and correlating by timestamp would not reliably reconstruct a single request's path."}, {"id": "observability-q-17", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "Trace Sampling", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "A team finds that capturing 100% of traces in their high-traffic production cluster creates too much data volume and cost. Which approach directly addresses this while keeping tracing useful?", "options": ["Apply sampling so that only a representative subset of traces is collected and stored", "Disable context propagation between services to reduce header overhead", "Switch all spans to log lines and rely on a logging backend instead", "Remove span attributes so each individual span uses less storage"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Sampling (head-based or tail-based) reduces trace volume and cost by recording only a subset of requests while still providing representative visibility. Disabling propagation would break trace correlation, converting to logs loses trace structure, and stripping attributes only shrinks each span slightly rather than reducing how many traces are collected."}, {"id": "observability-q-18", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "FinOps Fundamentals", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "What is the primary goal of FinOps (Cloud Financial Operations) in a cloud native environment?", "options": ["To eliminate all cloud spending by moving workloads back on-premises", "To bring financial accountability to cloud spending so teams can balance cost, speed, and quality", "To replace the engineering team's responsibility for infrastructure with a dedicated finance department", "To guarantee that cloud bills never increase from one month to the next"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "FinOps is a cultural and operational practice that brings financial accountability to variable cloud spending, enabling teams to make informed trade-offs between cost, speed, and quality. It is about optimizing and managing spend collaboratively, not eliminating it or freezing the bill."}, {"id": "observability-q-19", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "Cost Visibility and Allocation", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "In a multi-tenant Kubernetes cluster, which Kubernetes mechanism is most fundamental for attributing resource costs to specific teams or applications?", "options": ["Labels (and namespaces) applied to workloads", "Liveness probes on each pod", "TLS certificates issued to each service", "The cluster's DNS configuration"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Labels and namespaces let cost tooling group and allocate resource usage to specific teams, environments, or applications, which is the basis of cost showback/chargeback. Liveness probes, TLS certs, and DNS relate to health, security, and service discovery, not cost attribution."}, {"id": "observability-q-20", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "Kubernetes Cost Tooling", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "Which CNCF project is specifically designed to provide Kubernetes cost monitoring and allocation, helping teams understand the cost of namespaces, deployments, and labels?", "options": ["OpenCost", "CoreDNS", "Falco", "Argo CD"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "OpenCost is a CNCF project that provides real-time cost monitoring and allocation for Kubernetes workloads. CoreDNS handles cluster DNS, Falco is a runtime security tool, and Argo CD is a GitOps continuous delivery tool, none of which focus on cost."}, {"id": "observability-q-21", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "Resource Efficiency", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "A team sets CPU and memory requests far higher than what their pods actually use. From a FinOps perspective, what is the main consequence?", "options": ["Pods will be evicted immediately because requests exceed usage", "The scheduler reserves more cluster capacity than needed, reducing density and increasing cost", "Network egress charges rise sharply because of the larger requests", "Horizontal Pod Autoscaler is automatically disabled"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "The scheduler uses requests to reserve node capacity, so over-provisioned requests cause the cluster to reserve resources that sit idle, lowering bin-packing density and wasting money. Over-sized requests do not trigger eviction, change egress pricing, or disable the HPA."}, {"id": "observability-q-22", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "Cost Optimization Techniques", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "Which approach most directly reduces compute cost for fault-tolerant, interruptible batch workloads running on Kubernetes in a public cloud?", "options": ["Running every workload on on-demand instances with guaranteed QoS", "Using spot/preemptible instances for those workloads", "Increasing all resource limits to avoid throttling", "Disabling the cluster autoscaler to keep node count fixed"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "Spot/preemptible instances offer steep discounts in exchange for the possibility of interruption, making them ideal for fault-tolerant batch jobs. On-demand guarantees cost more, raising limits increases reservations, and disabling the autoscaler prevents scaling down to save money."}, {"id": "observability-q-23", "domainId": "observability", "topic": "FinOps Practices", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "In the FinOps Framework, which phase focuses on acting on cost data through workload right-sizing and rate optimization (such as committed-use discounts and spot instances)?", "options": ["Inform", "Optimize", "Operate", "Provision"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "The FinOps Foundation Framework defines three iterative phases: Inform (cost visibility, allocation, budgeting, and forecasting), Optimize (acting on the data through workload optimization like right-sizing and autoscaling, plus rate optimization like reservations and spot), and Operate (continuous governance, policy, and process). Right-sizing and rate optimization are the core Optimize activities. 'Provision' is not a FinOps phase."}]});
